<li id="lithub_daily_widget-9" class="widget widget_lithub_daily_widget"><div class="lithub-daily-header"><a href="/category/lit-hub-daily/"><b>Lithub</b> Daily</a></div><h2 class="widgettitle">January 16, 2024</h2>
<a href="/lit-hub-daily-january-16-2024/"><img class="wp-image-80541 size-thumbnail aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/Screen-Shot-2017-10-23-at-11.17.23-AM-150x150.png" alt="Tiya Miles" width="150" height="150" /></a>
<ul>
 	<li>Tiya Miles considers <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2024/01/octavia-butlers-guide-surviving-apocalypse/677106/" class="external" target="_blank">Octavia Butler’s “histofuturism.”</a></li>
 	<li>Viet Thanh Nguyen on <a href="https://www.esquire.com/lifestyle/a45855833/midlife-crisis-viet-thanh-nguyen/" class="external" target="_blank">embracing mid-life</a>.</li>
 	<li><a href="https://amp.theguardian.com/world/2024/jan/15/novelist-lana-bastasic-breaks-with-german-publisher-cultural-boycott-israel-gaza" class="external" target="_blank">Lana Bastašić broke with her German publisher</a> over censorship of pro-Palestinian voices.</li>
</ul>
